ment’."],"variants":[{"name":"Cliff","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Cliff(e), Cle(e)ve, or Clive, from Old English <i>clif</i> ‘slope, bank, cliff’, or a topographic name from the same word. The Old English word was used not only in the sense of modern English <i>cliff</i> but also of much gentler slopes and frequently also of a riverbank or seashore."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert De Clifton was born about 1138, in Clifton, Lancashire, England as the son of William De Clifton II and Clifton. He had at least 2 sons with Unknown. He died from 1154 to 1189, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1138–from 1154 to 1189":"umbes 1138–1154 kuni 1189","1138–1189":"1138–1189","1138–Female":"1138–Surnud","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1171–Male":"1171–Surnud","–1100":"–1100","1118–Female":"1118–Surnud","1118":"1118","1217":"1217","1138":"1138","about 1138":"umbes 1138","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","1171":"1171","1160":"1160","from 1154 to 1189":"1154 kuni 1189","Clifton, Lancashire, England":"Clifton, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1138–from 1154 to 1189":"noin 1138–vuodesta 1154 vuoteen 1189","1138–1189":"1138–1189","1138–Female":"1138–Kuollut","1160–1217":"1160–1217","1171–Male":"1171–Kuollut","–1100":"–1100","1118–Female":"1118–Kuollut","1118":"1118","1217":"1217","1138":"1138","about 1138":"noin 1138","1189":"118